<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-628-470  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 628 470.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Modern Office Technology  July 1990 v35 n7 p28(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What are the real costs of copying? (copiers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fernberg, Patricia M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users need to understand their copying requirements and evaluatemodels on the basis of cost, quality, service, speed, volume andversatility.andP;  By recording the number of copies made per month,users will get an idea of what their needs are.andP;  To calculate thecost per copy, users need to include such hidden costs asmaintenance, machine operation, tone, paper, drum or filmcartridges and service.andP;  Machine abuse such as using a low-volumemachine to consistently turn out more copies than it was designedfor leads to more frequent down-time, service calls andreplacement parts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CopyingGuidelinesHardware SelectionPerformance-Cost RelationshipUser NeedsCost Benefit Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>